    <h2>When to Use Which Strategy</h2>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Use Lump Sum When:</strong> The cash is meant for long-term growth (10+ years), you have a high risk tolerance, and you will not check your portfolio balance obsessively.</li>
      <li><strong>Use DCA When:</strong> You are investing a significant sum (relative to your net worth), the money represents an emotional windfall (like an inheritance), or you are investing during a period of extreme market volatility and need peace of mind.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-section">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Dollar cost averaging vs lump sum: Which is better mathematically?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Historically, lump sum investing outperforms dollar-cost averaging (DCA) approximately 68% of the time according to Vanguard. This is because stock markets tend to rise over the long term, so investing cash immediately gives it more time to compound. However, DCA provides a smoother ride and reduces the risk of investing everything right before a major crash.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Does dollar cost averaging work in a bear market?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes, DCA excels during bear markets or volatile periods. By investing a fixed amount on a regular schedule, you automatically purchase more shares when prices are low and fewer shares when prices are high. This lowers your average cost per share over time and provides psychological comfort when markets are dropping.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the DCA strategy explained in simple terms?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The DCA (Dollar-Cost Averaging) strategy involves investing a fixed amount of money at regular intervals (like $500 every month), regardless of what the stock market is doing. This removes the emotion from investing and eliminates the need to time the market.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Should I use dollar cost averaging vs lump sum for a windfall like an inheritance?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Mathematically, investing the lump sum immediately yields higher returns more often. However, if the fear of investing a large windfall right before a market drop would cause you severe anxiety, spreading the investments over 6 to 12 months using DCA is often the better psychological choice.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How often should I invest when using dollar cost averaging?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The frequency of your DCA strategy should generally align with when you receive income. For most investors, contributing bi-weekly or monthly straight from a paycheck is the most practical and effective approach.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
